%\section{Introduction}
Terrestrial forests are a major mitigation pathway for climate change, sequestering 20\% of greenhouse gas emissions   \citep{roe2021}. Most models of climate change assume warming will drive longer seasons, more tree growth and, thus, more carbon storage (Figure \ref{fig:cool1}a), following decades of evidence from ecosystem-scale studies \citep{White1999,Keenan2014}. 
However, recent findings from  observations of individual trees have questioned this assumption \citep{dow2022warm,silvestro2023longer}. At the same time new experiments on saplings have suggested that plants may adjust their end of season timing dynamically such that longer seasons do not increase total productivity (Figure \ref{fig:cool1}b), though the mechanism---and prevalence---of this effect is unclear \citep{Zani2020,Norby2021,Zohner2023},
