Differences between thermal and calendar growing seasons were strongest in the earlier-leafout species, which leaf out during the coolest part of the spring (Figure \ref{fig:cool1}-\ref{fig:vapar}). For later leafing species, earlier leafout did not substantially reduce their thermal growing season, bit it also did not increase it---suggesting thermal seasons do not increase with calendar growing seasons for any of our studied species. Species was the a major predictor of variation in leafout and budset% and growing season length 
