Beyond species-level variation, we found high variation across years in both leafout and budset. We expected large differences across years in leafout ($\sigma_{year}$: \Sexpr{sig.yr} days, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{sig.yr.l}, \Sexpr{sig.yr.h}], Figure \ref{fig:vapar}b), because it varies strongly with local climatic conditions---one of the reasons it is the most consistent biological indicator of anthropogenic climate change \citep{ipcc2022}. In line with this, we also found little variation across populations in leafout ($\sigma_{population}$: \Sexpr{sig.pop} days, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{sig.pop.l}, \Sexpr{sig.pop.h}], Figure \ref{fig:vapar}a). Yet our finding of 15 days of variation across years in budset was surprising (\sigma_{year}$: \Sexpr{bs.sig.yr} days, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{bs.sig.yr.l}, \Sexpr{bs.sig.yr.h}], Figure \ref{fig:vapar}b) because budset is generally thought to be strongly locally adapted and controlled by photoperiod, which does not vary year to year \citep{soolanayakanahally2013timing,aitken2016}. %dl15Nov2025: I would specify "local adaptation in budset" just to help the reader stay focused
